# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aleurites-moluccanus
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Humans first migrated to Australia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, and over time formed as many as 500 linguistic and territorial groups.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal people once lived across large areas of the continental shelf that were later inundated by postglacial sea-level rise at the start of the Holocene inter-glacial period, reshaping coastal landscapes and separating Tasmania from the mainland.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal people maintained extensive networks within the continent and certain groups maintained relationships with Torres Strait Islanders and the Makassar people of modern-day Indonesia.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Over the millennia, Aboriginal people developed complex trade networks, inter-cultural relationships, law and religions, which make up some of the oldest continuous cultures in the world.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] At the time of European colonisation of Australia, the Aboriginal people spoke more than 250 different languages, possessed varying degrees of technology, and lived in various types of settlements.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Languages (or dialects) and language-associated groups of people are connected with stretches of territory known as "Country", with which they have a profound spiritual connection.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Contemporary Aboriginal beliefs are shaped by traditional beliefs, the disruption of colonisation, religions brought to the continent by later migrants, and contemporary issues.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Just over half hold secular or other spiritual beliefs or no religious affiliation; about 40% are Christian; and about 1% adhere to a traditional Aboriginal religion.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Traditional cultural beliefs are passed down and shared through dancing, stories, songlines, and art that collectively weave an ontology of modern daily life and ancient creation known as the Dreaming.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Studies of Aboriginal groups' genetic makeup are ongoing, but evidence suggests that they have genetic inheritance from ancient Asian peoples.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians and Papuans shared the same paleocontinent Sahul, although they became genetically distinct about 37,000 years ago.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians have a broadly shared, complex genetic history, but only in the last 200 years have they been defined by others as, and started to self-identify as, a single group.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal identity has changed over time and place, with family lineage, self-identification, and community acceptance all of varying importance.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] The 2021 census shows that there were 944,171 Aboriginal people, comprising 3.7% of Australia's population.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Over 80% of Aboriginal people today speak English at home, and about 77,000 speak an Indigenous language at home.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal people, along with Torres Strait Islander people, suffer a number of severe health and economic deprivations in comparison with the wider Australian community.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Archeological evidence indicates that the ancestors of today's Aboriginal Australians first migrated to the continent 50,000 to 65,000 years ago.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] While there have been genomic studies placing arrival as late as 43,000 years ago, a 2025 study suggests that the peopling of Australia happened around 60,000 years ago, via two distinct routes.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Early human migration to Australia was achieved when it formed a part of the Sahul continent, connected to the island of New Guinea via a land bridge.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] This would have nevertheless required crossing the sea at the Wallace Line.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] It is also possible that people came by island-hopping via an island chain between Sulawesi and New Guinea, reaching North Western Australia via Timor.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] As sea levels rose, the people on the Australian mainland and nearby islands became increasingly isolated, some on Tasmania and some of the smaller offshore islands when the land was inundated at the start of the Holocene, the inter-glacial period that started about 11,700 years ago.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] The modelling is based on data from archaeologists, anthropologists, ecologists, geneticists, climatologists, geomorphologists, and hydrologists.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] The new models suggest that the first people may have landed in the Kimberley region in what is now Western Australia about 60,000 years ago, and had settled across the continent within 6,000 years.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians may have one of the oldest continuous cultures on earth.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] In Arnhem Land in the Northern Territory, oral histories comprising complex narratives have been passed down by Yolngu people through hundreds of generations.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] The Aboriginal rock art, dated by modern techniques, shows that their culture has continued from ancient times.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Genetic studies have revealed that a population wave, termed East Eurasian Core, outgoing from the Iranian plateau during the Initial Upper Paleolithic period populated the Asia-Pacific region via a southern route dispersal.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] This wave is suggested to have expanded into the South and Southeast Asia region and subsequently diverged rapidly into the ancestors of Ancient Ancestral South Indians (AASI), Andamanese, East Asians, and Australasians, including Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians are genetically most closely related to other Oceanians, such as Papuans and Melanesians, who are collectively referred to as "Australasians," which can be described as "a deeply branching East Asian lineage".
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] This earlier group has been estimated to have possibly contributed around 2% ancestry to modern Aboriginal Australians.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] 2017 found the bifurcation of Eastern Eurasians and Western Eurasians dates to at least 45,000 years ago, with indigenous Australians nested inside the Eastern Eurasian clade.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Genetic data on indigenous populations of Borneo and Malaysia showed them to be more closely related to other mainland Asian groups, than compared to the groups from Papua New Guinea and Australia.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] This indicates that populations in Australia were isolated for a long time from the rest of Southeast Asia.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] They remained untouched by migrations and population expansions into that area, which can be explained by the Wallace line.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] The most common Y-chromosome haplogroups among Aboriginal Australians is C1b2, followed by haplogroups S and M; these latter haplogroups are also very frequent among Papuans.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] In a 2001 study, blood samples were collected from some Warlpiri people in the Northern Territory to study their genetic makeup (which is not representative of all Aboriginal peoples in Australia).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] The study concluded that the Warlpiri are descended from ancient Asians whose DNA is still somewhat present in Southeastern Asian groups, although greatly diminished.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] The Warlpiri DNA lacks certain information found in modern Asian genomes, and carries information not found in other genomes.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] This reinforces the idea of ancient Aboriginal isolation.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Genetic data extracted in 2011 by Morten Rasmussen et al., who took a DNA sample from an early-20th-century lock of an Aboriginal person's hair, found that the Aboriginal ancestors probably migrated through South Asia and Maritime Southeast Asia, into Australia, where they stayed.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] As a result, outside of Africa, the Aboriginal peoples have continuously occupied the same territory longer than any other human populations.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] These findings suggest that modern Aboriginal Australians are the direct descendants of the eastern wave, who left Africa up to 75,000 years ago.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Examining DNA from a finger bone excavated in Siberia, researchers concluded that the Denisovans migrated from Siberia to tropical parts of Asia and that they interbred with modern humans in Southeast Asia 44,000 years BP, before Australia separated from New Guinea approximately 11,700 years BP.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] They contributed DNA to Aboriginal Australians and to present-day New Guineans and an indigenous tribe in the Philippines known as Mamanwa.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] This study confirms Aboriginal Australians as one of the oldest living populations in the world.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] They are possibly the oldest outside Africa, and they may have the oldest continuous culture on the planet.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] A 2016 study at the University of Cambridge suggests that it was about 50,000 years ago that these peoples reached Sahul (the supercontinent consisting of present-day Australia and its islands and New Guinea).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] The sea levels rose and isolated Australia about 10,000 years ago, but Aboriginal Australians and Papuans diverged from each other earlier, genetically, about 37,000 years BP, possibly because the remaining land bridge was impassable.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] This isolation makes the Aboriginal people the world's oldest culture.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] The study also found evidence of an unknown hominin group, distantly related to Denisovans, with whom the Aboriginal and Papuan ancestors must have interbred, leaving a trace of about 4% in most Aboriginal Australians' genome.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] There is, however, increased genetic diversity among Aboriginal Australians based on geographical distribution.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] 2021 analysed a Holocene hunter-gatherer sample ("Leang Panninge") from South Sulawesi, which shares high amounts of genetic drift with Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] This suggests that a population split from the common ancestor of Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] The sample also shows genetic affinity with East Asians and the Andamanese people of South Asia.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] The authors note that this hunter-gatherer sample can be modelled with ~50% Australian/Papuan-related ancestry and either with ~50% East Asian or Andamanese Onge ancestry, highlighting the deep split between Leang Panninge and Aboriginal/Papuans.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] 2021 found that Philippines Negrito people split from the common ancestor of Aboriginal Australians and Papuans before the latter two diverged from each other, but after their common ancestor diverged from the ancestor of East Asian peoples.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Like Papuans, it's believed that Aboriginal Australians underwent a secondary admixture event with Altai-related Denisovan populations after they diverged from the ancestors of East Asians, who already mixed with Denisovans.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] This event was also separate from the admixture event experienced by Filipino Negritos, explaining why Aboriginal Australians and Papuans have relatively lower Denisovan ancestry.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Based on a reevaluation of mitogenomes, Gandini et al.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] 2025 proposed a "long chronology", which suggested an earlier settlement of Sahul by two migration routes about ~60 ka.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] One route came from northern Sunda via the Philippine archipelago whilst the other came from southern Sunda via Mainland Southeast Asia, with both routes ultimately tracing back to South Asia.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] The settlers that undertook these routes were ancestral to populations indigenous to Australia, New Guinea and Oceania, and were also related to other East Eurasians instead of belonging to a separate wave.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] The dingo reached Australia about 4,000 years ago.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Near that time, there were changes in language (with the Pama-Nyungan language family spreading over most of the mainland), and in stone tool technology.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] The first type of evidence comes from a 2013 study by the Max Planck Institute for Evolutionary Anthropology using large-scale genotyping data from a pool of Aboriginal Australians, New Guineans, island Southeast Asians, and Indians.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] It found that the New Guinea and Mamanwa (Philippines area) groups diverged from the Aboriginal about 36,000 years ago (there is supporting evidence that these populations are descended from migrants taking an early "southern route" out of Africa, before other groups in the area).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Also the Indian and Australian populations mixed long before European contact, with this gene flow occurring during the Holocene (c.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] The researchers had two theories for this: either some Indians had contact with people in Indonesia who eventually transferred those Indian genes to Aboriginal Australians, or a group of Indians migrated from India to Australia and intermingled with the locals directly.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] However, a 2016 study in *Current Biology* by Anders Bergström et al. excluded the Y chromosome as providing evidence for recent gene flow from India into Australia.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] The study authors sequenced 13 Aboriginal Australian Y chromosomes using recent advances in gene sequencing technology.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] They investigated their divergence times from Y chromosomes in other continents, including comparing the haplogroup C chromosomes.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] They found a divergence time of about 54,100 years between the Sahul C chromosome and its closest relative C5, as well as about 54,300 years between haplogroups K*/M and their closest haplogroups R and Q.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] The deep divergence time of 50,000-plus years with the South Asian chromosome and "the fact that the Aboriginal Australian Cs share a more recent common ancestor with Papuan Cs" excludes any recent genetic contact.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] They attributed the disparity between their results and previous findings to improvements in technology; none of the other studies had utilised complete Y chromosome sequencing, which has the highest precision.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] For example, use of a ten Y STRs method has been shown to massively underestimate divergence times.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Bergström's 2018 doctoral thesis looking at the population of Sahul suggests that other than relatively recent admixture, the populations of the region appear to have been genetically independent from the rest of the world since their divergence about 50,000 years ago.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] He writes "There is no evidence for South Asian gene flow to Australia ....
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians possess inherited abilities to adapt to a wide range of environmental temperatures in various ways.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] A study in 1958 comparing cold adaptation in the desert-dwelling Pitjantjatjara people compared with a group of European people showed that the cooling adaptation of the Aboriginal group differed from that of the Europeans, and that they were able to sleep more soundly through a cold desert night.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] A 2014 Cambridge University study found that a beneficial mutation in two genes that regulate thyroxine, a hormone involved in regulating body metabolism, helps to regulate body temperature in response to fever.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] The effect of this is that the desert people are able to have a higher body temperature without accelerating the activity of the whole of the body, which can be especially detrimental in childhood diseases.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] This helps protect people to survive the side-effects of infection.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] It is estimated that the Indigenous Australian population at the time of first European settlement numbered at least 314,500 people.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Based on the 2021 census, the Australian Bureau of Statistics estimates there were 901,655 Aboriginal Australians, and 42,516 who identified as both Aboriginal Australian and Torres Strait Islander.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] These groups comprise 3.7% of the total Australian population.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] 39,538 people identified as Torres Strait Islander, which is a different ethnic group from Aboriginal Australian.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Based on initial 2021 census counts, the Aboriginal and Torres Strait islander population grew 25.2%, since the previous census in 2016.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Demographic factors – births, deaths and migration – accounted for 43.5% of the increase (71,086 people).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] In turn, 76.2% of that increase was attributed to people aged 0–19 years in 2021, broken down as 52.5% for 0–4 year olds (births since 2016) and 23.7% for 5–19 year olds.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Reasons for the increase in Aboriginal population also include non-demographic factors.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] These include changes in individuals' identification as Aboriginal or Torres Strait Islander in different censuses, and individuals completing a census form in 2021 but not in 2016.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] These factors accounted for 56.5% of the increase in the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander population.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Indigenous Australians (including Torres Strait Islanders) are less likely to live in the major Australian cities than are non-Indigenous Australians (41% compared with 73%).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Although humans arrived in Australia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, it is possible that the ancestor language of existing Aboriginal languages is as recent as 12,000 years old.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Over 250 Australian Aboriginal languages are thought to have existed at the time of first European contact.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] As of 2021, 84% of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islanders spoke only English at home.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] The National Indigenous Languages Survey (NILS) for 2018-19 found that more than 120 Indigenous language varieties were in use or being revived, although 70 of those in use are endangered.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] The 2021 census found that 167 Indigenous languages were spoken at home by 76,978 Indigenous Australians.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] NILS and the Australian Bureau of Statistics use different classifications for Indigenous Australian languages.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] According to the 2021 census, the classifiable Aboriginal languages with the most speakers are Kriol (7,403), Djambarrpuyngu (3,839), Pitjantjatjara (3,399), Warlpiri (2,592), Murrinh Patha (2,063) and Tiwi (2,053).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] There were also over 10,000 people who spoke an Indigenous language that could not be further defined or classified.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] A number of English-based creoles have arisen in Australia after European contact, of which Kriol is among the strongest and fastest-growing Aboriginal languages.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Kriol is spoken in the Northern Territory and Western Australia.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] It is estimated that there are 20,000 to 30,000 speakers of Indigenous creole languages.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Before British colonisation, there were perhaps five to sixteen languages on Tasmania, possibly related to one another in four language families.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] The last speaker of a traditional Tasmanian language, Fanny Cochrane Smith, died in 1905.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Palawa kani is an in-progress constructed language, built from a composite of surviving words from various Tasmanian Aboriginal languages.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Traditional Indigenous languages often incorporated sign systems to aid communication with the hearing impaired, to complement verbal communication, and to replace verbal communication when the spoken language was forbidden for cultural reasons.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Many of these sign systems are still in use.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Dispersing across the Australian continent over time, the ancient people expanded and differentiated into distinct groups, each with its own language and culture.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] More than 400 distinct Australian Aboriginal peoples have been identified, distinguished by names designating their ancestral languages, dialects, or distinctive speech patterns.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] According to noted anthropologist, archaeologist and sociologist Harry Lourandos, historically, these groups lived in three main cultural areas, the Northern, Southern and Central cultural areas.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] The Northern and Southern areas, having richer natural marine and woodland resources, were more densely populated than the Central area.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Other group names are based on the language group or specific dialect spoken.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] These also coincide with geographical regions of varying sizes.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] However, these lists are neither exhaustive nor definitive, and there are overlaps.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Different approaches have been taken by non-Aboriginal scholars in trying to understand and define Aboriginal culture and societies, some focusing on the micro-level (tribe, clan, etc.), and others on shared languages and cultural practices spread over large regions defined by ecological factors.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Anthropologists have encountered many difficulties in trying to define what constitutes an Aboriginal people/community/group/tribe, let alone naming them.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Knowledge of pre-colonial Aboriginal cultures and societal groupings is still largely dependent on the observers' interpretations, which were filtered through colonial ways of viewing societies.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Some Aboriginal peoples identify as one of several saltwater, freshwater, rainforest or desert peoples.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] The term *Aboriginal Australians* includes many distinct peoples who have developed across Australia for over 50,000 years.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] These peoples have a broadly shared, complex, genetic history, but it is only in the last two hundred years that they have been defined and have started to self-identify as a single group socio-politically.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] While some preferred the term *Aborigine* to *Aboriginal* in the past, as the latter was seen to have more directly discriminatory legal origins, use of the term *Aborigine* has declined in recent decades, as many consider the term an offensive and racist hangover from Australia's colonial era.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] The definition of the term *Aboriginal* has changed over time and place, with family lineage, self-identification and community acceptance all being of varying importance.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] The term *Indigenous Australians* refers to Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islander peoples, and the term is conventionally only used when both groups are included in the topic being addressed, or by self-identification by a person as Indigenous.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] As of 2021, 51% of Indigenous people stated that they held a secular or other spiritual belief or no religious affiliation; 41% were affiliated to Christianity; and 1% were affiliated to a traditional Aboriginal religion.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Australian Indigenous people have beliefs unique to each mob (tribe) and have a strong connection to the land.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Contemporary Indigenous Australian beliefs are a complex mixture, varying by region and individual across the continent.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] They are shaped by traditional beliefs, the disruption of colonisation, religions brought to the continent by Europeans, and contemporary issues.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Traditional cultural beliefs are passed down and shared by dancing, stories, songlines and art—especially Papunya Tula (dot painting)—collectively telling the story of creation known as The Dreamtime.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Additionally, traditional healers were also custodians of important Dreaming stories as well as their medical roles (for example the Ngangkari in the Western desert).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Some core structures and themes are shared across the continent with details and additional elements varying between language and cultural groups.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] For example, in The Dreamtime of most regions, a spirit creates the earth then tells the humans to treat the animals and the earth in a way that is respectful to land.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] In Northern Territory this spirit is commonly said to be a huge snake or snakes that weaved its way through the earth and sky making the mountains and oceans.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] But in other places the spirits who created the world are known as wandjina rain and water spirits.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Major ancestral spirits include the Rainbow Serpent, Baiame, Dirawong and Bunjil.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Similarly, the Arrernte people of central Australia believed that humanity originated from great superhuman ancestors who brought the sun, wind and rain as a result of breaking through the surface of the Earth when waking from their slumber.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Many Dreamtime stories are still believed by many Indigenous Australians to this day.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Taken as a whole, Aboriginal Australians, along with Torres Strait Islander people, have a number of health and economic deprivations in comparison with the wider Australian community.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Due to the aforementioned disadvantage, Aboriginal Australian communities experience a higher rate of suicide, as compared to non-indigenous communities.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] These issues stem from a variety of different causes unique to indigenous communities, such as historical trauma, socioeconomic disadvantage, and decreased access to education and health care.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Also, this problem largely affects indigenous youth, as many indigenous youth may feel disconnected from their culture.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] To combat the increased suicide rate, many researchers have suggested that the inclusion of more cultural aspects into suicide prevention programs would help to combat mental health issues within the community.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Past studies have found that many indigenous leaders and community members, do in fact, want more culturally-aware health care programs.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Similarly, culturally-relative programs targeting indigenous youth have actively challenged suicide ideation among younger indigenous populations, with many social and emotional wellbeing programs using cultural information to provide coping mechanisms and improving mental health.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] Indigenous communities in remote Australia are often small, isolated towns with basic facilities, on traditionally owned land.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] These communities have between 20 and 300 inhabitants and are often closed to outsiders for cultural reasons.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aboriginal-australians] The long-term viability and resilience of Aboriginal communities in desert areas has been discussed by scholars and policy-makers.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] The **acorn** is the nut of the oaks and their close relatives (genera *Quercus*, *Notholithocarpus* and *Lithocarpus*, in the family Fagaceae); alternatively known as **glans**.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] It usually contains a seedling surrounded by two cotyledons (seedling leaves), enclosed in a tough shell known as the pericarp, and borne in a cup-shaped cupule.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Acorns take between 5 and 24 months (depending on the species) to mature; see the list of *Quercus* species for details of oak classification, in which acorn morphology and phenology are important factors.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] The word *acorn* (earlier *akerne*, and *acharn*) is related to the Gothic name *akran*, which had the sense of "fruit of the unenclosed land".
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] The word was applied to the most important forest produce, that of the oak.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Chaucer spoke of "achornes of okes" in the 14th century.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] By degrees, popular etymology connected the word both with "corn" and "oak-horn", and the spelling changed accordingly.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] 15th–16th century) derives from association with *ac* (Old English: "oak") + *corn*.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] The Latin *glans* as found in many literature regarding it originally applies to any nut is the root of several Romance words for the acorn (the French *gland*, Catalan *gla*, Italian *ghianda*) cognate to Greek βάλανος, which also extends to the vascular penile tip from similarity in shape.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Acorns play an important role in forest ecology when oaks are plentiful or dominant in the landscape.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] The volume of the acorn crop may vary widely, creating great abundance or great stress on the many animals dependent on acorns and the predators of those animals.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Acorns, along with other nuts, are termed mast.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Wildlife that consume acorns as an important part of their diets include birds, such as jays, pigeons, some ducks, and several species of woodpeckers.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Small mammals that feed on acorns include mice, squirrels and several other rodents.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] One beetle species, *Thorectes lusitanicus*, also feeds on acorns.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Acorns have a large influence on small rodents in their habitats, as large acorn yields help rodent populations to grow.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Large mammals such as pigs, bears, and deer also consume large amounts of acorns; they may constitute up to 25% of the diet of deer in the autumn.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] In Spain, Portugal and the New Forest region of southern England, pigs are still turned loose in *dehesas* (large oak groves) in the autumn, to fill and fatten themselves on acorns.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Heavy consumption of acorns can, on the other hand, be toxic to other animals that cannot detoxify their tannins, such as horses and cattle, especially if eaten in excess.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] The larvae of some moths and weevils also live in young acorns, consuming the kernels as they develop.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Acorns are attractive to animals because they are large and thus efficiently consumed or cached.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Percentages vary from species to species, but all acorns contain large amounts of protein, carbohydrates and fats, as well as the minerals calcium, phosphorus and potassium, and the vitamin niacin.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Total food energy in an acorn also varies by species, but all compare well with other wild foods and with other nuts.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Acorns also contain bitter tannins, the amount varying with the species.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Since tannins, which are plant polyphenols, interfere with an animal's ability to metabolize protein, creatures must adapt in different ways to use the nutritional value acorns contain.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Animals may preferentially select acorns that contain fewer tannins.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] When the tannins are metabolized in cattle, the tannic acid produced can cause ulceration and kidney failure.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Animals that cache acorns, such as jays and squirrels, may wait to consume some of these acorns until sufficient groundwater has percolated through them to leach out the tannins.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Other animals buffer their acorn diet with other foods.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Many insects, birds, and mammals metabolize tannins with fewer ill effects than do humans.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Species of acorn that contain large amounts of tannins are very bitter, astringent, and potentially irritating if eaten raw.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] This is particularly true of the acorns of American red oaks and English oaks.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] The acorns of white oaks, being much lower in tannins, are nutty in flavor; this characteristic is enhanced if the acorns are given a light roast before grinding.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Tannins can be removed by soaking chopped acorns in several changes of water, until the water no longer turns brown.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Cold water leaching can take several days, but three to four changes of boiling water can leach the tannins in under an hour.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Hot water leaching (boiling) cooks the starch of the acorn, which would otherwise act like gluten in flour, helping it bind to itself.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] For this reason, if the acorns will be used to make flour, then cold water leaching is preferred.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Being rich in fat, acorn flour can spoil or molder easily and must be carefully stored.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Acorns are also sometimes prepared as a massage oil.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Acorns of the white oak group, *Leucobalanus*, typically start rooting as soon as they are in contact with the soil (in the fall), then send up the leaf shoot in the spring.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Acorns are too heavy for wind dispersal, so they require other ways to spread.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Oaks therefore depend on biological seed dispersal agents to move the acorns beyond the mother tree and into a suitable area for germination (including access to adequate water, sunlight and soil nutrients), ideally a minimum of 20–30 m (70–100 ft) from the parent tree.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Many animals eat unripe acorns on the tree or ripe acorns from the ground, with no reproductive benefit to the oak, but some animals, such as squirrels and jays serve as seed dispersal agents.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Jays and squirrels that scatter-hoard acorns in caches for future use effectively plant acorns in a variety of locations in which it is possible for them to germinate and thrive.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Even though jays and squirrels retain remarkably large mental maps of cache locations and return to eat them, the odd acorn may be lost, or a jay or squirrel may die before consuming all of its stores.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] A small number of acorns manage to germinate and survive, producing the next generation of oaks.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Scatter-hoarding behavior depends on jays and squirrels associating with plants that provide good packets of food that are nutritionally valuable, but not too big for the dispersal agent to handle.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] The beak sizes of jays determine how large acorns may get before jays ignore them.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Acorns germinate on different schedules, depending on their place in the oak family.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Once acorns sprout, they are less nutritious, as the seed tissue converts to the indigestible lignins that form the root.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] In some cultures, acorns once constituted a dietary staple, though they have largely been replaced by grains and are now typically considered a relatively unimportant food, except in some Native American and Korean communities.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Several cultures have devised traditional acorn-leaching methods, sometimes involving specialized tools, that were traditionally passed on to their children by word of mouth.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Raw acorns are 28% water, 41% carbohydrates, 24% fat, and 6% protein (table).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] In a reference amount of 100 g (3.5 oz), raw acorns supply 387 calories and are a rich source (20% or more of the Daily Value, DV) of vitamin B6, folate, copper, and manganese (table).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Acorns served an important role in early human history and were a source of food for many cultures around the world.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Dental microwear suggests that Neanderthals in Belgium consumed acorns among other hard foods.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Many modern human cultures relied on acorns, such as the Ancient Greek lower classes and the Japanese (during the Jōmon period), for instance.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] In antiquity, Pliny the Elder noted that acorn flour could be used to make bread.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Acorns rarely form a large part of modern diets and are not currently cultivated on scales approaching that of many other nuts.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] However, if properly prepared (by selecting high-quality specimens and leaching out the bitter tannins in water), acorn meal can be used in some recipes calling for grain flours.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Varieties of oak differ in the amount of tannin in their acorns.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Varieties preferred by Native Americans, such as *Quercus kelloggii* (California black oak), may be easier to prepare or more palatable.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Roasted acorn flour is a main ingredient in sweet cakes special to Kurdish areas of Iran and Iraq.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Acorns are a traditional food of many indigenous peoples of North America, and long served an especially important role for Californian Native Americans, where the ranges of several species of oaks overlap, increasing the reliability of the resource.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] In the San Francisco Bay Area acorns found were often associated with grinding tools.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Stone tools like hammerstone and anvil, millingstones, and mortar and pestle help crack open the acorn and grind the acorn into dust.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Acorns and balanophagy (acorn-eating [fr]) were associated with ideas of primitive life and Arcadia in classical literature and beyond.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] A motif in Roman architecture, also popular in Celtic and Scandinavian art, the acorn symbol is used as an ornament on cutlery, furniture, and jewelry; it also appears on finials at Westminster Abbey.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] The acorn was used frequently by both Union and Confederate forces during the American Civil War.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Modern US Army Cavalry Scout campaign hats still retain traces of the acorn today.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] The acorn is the symbol for the National Trails of England and Wales, and is used for the waymarks on these paths.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] The acorn, specifically that of the white oak, is also present in the symbol for the University of Connecticut.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/acorn] Acorns are also used as charges in heraldry.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] The **Agricultural Research Service** (**ARS**) is the principal in-house research agency of the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] ARS is one of four agencies in USDA's Research, Education and Economics mission area.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] ARS is charged with extending the nation's scientific knowledge and solving agricultural problems through its four national program areas: nutrition, food safety and quality; animal production and protection; natural resources and sustainable agricultural systems; and crop production and protection.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] ARS research focuses on solving problems affecting Americans every day.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] The ARS Headquarters is located in the Jamie L.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] Whitten Building on Independence Avenue in Washington, D.C., and the headquarters staff is located at the George Washington Carver Center (GWCC) in Beltsville, Maryland.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] For 2023, the budget grew to $1.9 billion.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] ARS conducts scientific research for the American public.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] ARS research complements the work of state colleges and universities, agricultural experiment stations, other federal and state agencies, and the private sector.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] ARS research may often focus on regional issues that have national implications, and where there is a clear federal role.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] ARS also provides information on its research results to USDA action and regulatory agencies and to several other federal regulatory agencies, including the Food and Drug Administration and the United States Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] ARS disseminates much of its research results through scientific journals, technical publications, *Agricultural Research* magazine, and other forums.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] Information is also distributed through ARS's National Agricultural Library (NAL).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] ARS has more than 150 librarians and other information specialists who work at two NAL locations—the Abraham Lincoln Building in Beltsville, Maryland; and the DC Reference Center in Washington, D.C.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] NAL provides reference and information services, document delivery, interlibrary loan and interlibrary borrowing services to a variety of audiences.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] Prior to the inception of ARS, agricultural research was first conducted under the umbrella of the Agricultural Department in the U.S.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] It was created to collect statistics, distribute seeds and compile and distribute pertinent information.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] In 1862 the USDA was created and agricultural research was moved to its department.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] That same year, the department issued its first research bulletin on the sugar content of grape varietals and their suitability for wine.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] Six years later the USDA would begin its first research on animal diseases, specifically hog cholera, which was causing devastating losses at the time.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] In the early 1900s the USDA began analyzing food composition and the first studies of nutrition and the effects of cooking and processing foods were conducted.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] Finally, in 1953 the Agricultural Research Service was created to be the USDA's primary scientific research agency.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] ARS supports more than 2,000 scientists and post docs working on approximately 690 research projects within 15 National Programs at more than 90 research locations.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] The ARS is divided into 5 geographic areas: Midwest Area, Northeast Area, Pacific West Area, Plains Area, and Southeast Area.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] The research centers focus on innovation in agricultural practices, pest control, health, and nutrition among other things.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] Work at these facilities has given life to numerous products, processes, and technologies.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] Wallace Beltsville Agricultural Research Center (BARC) in Beltsville, Maryland, is the world's largest agricultural research complex.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] Other D.C. area locations include the United States National Agricultural Library and the United States National Arboretum.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] ARS also has six major human nutrition research centers that focus on solving a wide spectrum of human nutrition questions by providing authoritative, peer-reviewed, science-based evidence.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] The centers are located in Arkansas, Maryland, Texas, North Dakota, Massachusetts (the Human Nutrition Research Center on Aging), and California.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] ARS scientists at these centers study the role of food and dietary components in human health from conception to advanced age.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] The ARS also offers the Culture Collection, which is the largest public collection of microorganisms in the world, containing approximately 93,000 strains of bacteria and fungi.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] The ARS Culture Collection is housed at the National Center for Agricultural Utilization Research (NCAUR).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] There is also a collection of entomopathogenic fungi, called ARSEF, at the Robert W.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] Holley Center for Agriculture and Health in Ithaca, New York.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] Horticultural Research Laboratory in Fort Pierce, Florida, and the U.S.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] National Poultry Research Center in Athens, Georgia.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] Other notable ARS facilities include Northern Great Basin Experimental Range in Oregon, and formerly the Plum Island Animal Disease Center off Long Island.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] Several ARS research units focus on pests, diseases, and management practices of horticultural crops.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] The Cereal Disease Laboratory is located on the campus of the University of Minnesota in Saint Paul.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] It primarily hosts research into rusts and *Fusaria* of cereals.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] The San Joaquin Valley Agricultural Sciences Center in Parlier, California conducts research on specialty crops including grapes, citrus, almonds, alfalfa, peaches, pomegranates, and many others.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] Several research locations throughout the US also house germplasm collections of plant species important for agricultural and industrial uses as part of the **National Genetic Resources Program**.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] From the very beginning the Department of Agriculture and in turn the Agricultural Research Service has been focused on improving not only the farming industry but also the quality of food and the health of Americans.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] In 1985, technology to produce lactose-free milk, yogurt, and ice cream was developed through the Agricultural Research Service.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] The grape breeding program, currently located in Parlier, CA which began in 1923, developed seedless grapes and continues to release new grapevine varieties with improved traits.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] The ARS Citrus and Subtropical Products Laboratory in Winter Haven, Florida, actively works to improve the taste of orange juice concentrate.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] The Agricultural Research Service had a *Toxoplasma gondii* (*T. gondii*) research program, which experimented on cats infected with the parasite, from 1982 until 2018.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] The prevalence of *T. gondii* parasite has been reduced by 50% in the U.S.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] As of September 2018, which the ARS claims is a result of their research.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] The USDA has since discontinued the use of cats in their research amid acute accusations of animal abuse, and a lack of meaningful contribution to the field in recent years (only three of thirteen papers published about *T. gondii* by the ARS were published after the year 2000).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] More recently, the ARS has focused research on genetics and plant and animal DNA.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] Their research has developed pest-resistant corn, faster growing plants and fish, and a focus on plant and animal genome research and mapping.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/agricultural-research-service] Outside of scientific research, the ARS has worked to release databases on food components in order to assist consumers with making informed decisions about food choices.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] First described by Carl Linnaeus in 1753, the species' origin is unclear due to its spread by humans, but it can be found in many tropical rainforests and gallery forests.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] Various parts of the plant have regional or cultural uses.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] The candlenut tree grows to a height of up to 30 m (98 ft), with wide spreading or pendulous branches.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] The leaves are pale green, simple, and ovate or heart-shaped on mature shoots, but may be three-, five-, or seven-lobed on saplings.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] They are up to 20 cm (8 in) long and 13 cm (5 in) wide and young leaves are densely clothed in rusty or cream stellate hairs.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] Petioles measure up to 12.5 cm (5 in) long and stipules about 5 mm (1⁄4 in).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] The flowers are small; male flowers measure around 5 mm in diameter, female flowers about 9 mm.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] The fruit is a drupe about 4–6 cm (1+1⁄2–2+1⁄4 in) in diameter with one or two lobes; each lobe has a single soft, white, oily kernel contained within a hard shell about 2 cm (3⁄4 in) in diameter.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] These nuts, upon germinating, produce cotyledons or seed leaves up to 9 cm (3.5 in) long by 5.5 cm (2.2 in) wide.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] This plant was first described by Carl Linnaeus in his *Species Plantarum* (1753) as *Jatropha moluccana*.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] It was renamed as *Aleurites moluccana* by Carl Ludwig Willdenow in an 1805 edition of *Species Plantarum*, but the ending was corrected to match the gender of the Latin genus *Aleurites moluccanus*.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] While there are many online references to the spelling "Aleurites moluccana", this is not accepted by botanical authorities such as the International Plant Names Index or the Germplasm Resources Information Network.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] The genus name derives from the Ancient Greek ἄλευρον (*áleuron*), meaning "flour" or "meal", and refers to the new growth which appears to be dusted with flour.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] The species epithet means "from the Moluccas".
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] Its native range is impossible to establish precisely because of early spread by humans, and the tree is now distributed throughout the New and Old World tropics including the Indian subcontinent, Southeast Asia, Papuasia, Queensland in Australia, and some islands of the western Pacific Ocean.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] The candlenut was first domesticated on the islands of Southeast Asia.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] Remains of harvested candlenuts have been recovered from archaeological sites in Timor and Morotai in eastern Indonesia, dated to around 13,000 and 11,000 BP, respectively.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] Archaeological evidence of candlenut cultivation is also found in Neolithic sites of the Toalean culture in southern Sulawesi dated to around 3,700 to 2,300 BP.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] Early Austronesian voyagers introduced candlenuts, as a canoe plant, widely across the Pacific islands; the trees became naturalized to high volcanic islands.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] In Australia the seeds are eaten by rodents, in particular the giant white-tailed rat.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] The broken shells of the fruits are often found underneath the trees.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] The larvae of the coleopteran *Agrianome fairmairei* feed on dead candlenut wood, and are considered a delicacy in New Caledonia.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] Because the seeds contain saponin, phorbol, and toxalbumins, they are mildly toxic when raw, inducing a laxative effect.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] Heat treatment reduces the toxicity of the protein component.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] While mildly toxic when raw, the nut is appreciated in many cultures once cooked or toasted.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] In Indonesian and Malaysian cuisine, it is commonly used in curries, and on the Indonesian island of Java, it is used to make a thick sauce that is eaten with vegetables and rice.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] A Hawaiian condiment known as *ʻinamona* is made from roasted kukui mixed into a paste with salt.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] *ʻInamona* is a key ingredient in traditional Hawaiian *poke*.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] The kernel is the source of candlenut oil, which has no known toxicity and is not an irritant, even to the eyes.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] In ancient Hawaiʻi, kukui fruits were burned to provide light.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] The nuts were strung in a row on a palm leaf midrib, lit on one end, and burned one by one every fifteen minutes or so.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] This led to their use as a measure of time.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] Hawaiians extracted the oil from the nut and burned it in a stone oil lamp called a *kukui hele po* (light, darkness goes) with a wick made of *kapa* cloth.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] A red-brown dye made from the inner bark was used on *kapa* and *aho* (*Touchardia latifolia* cordage).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] A coating of kukui oil helped preserve *ʻupena* (fishing nets).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] The *nohona waʻa* (seats) and *pale* (gunwales) of *waʻa* (outrigger canoes) were made from the wood.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] The trunk was sometimes used to make smaller canoes used for fishing.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] The oil can often be found in Indonesian hair-care products.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] In Fiji, where the nut is called *sikeci*, the oil is used in cosmetic products.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] Wealthier members of the Batak people have their coffins (Karo: *pelangkah*) made from the wood, carved in the shape of a boat whose bow is decorated with the carved head of a hornbill, a horse, or a mythical beast known as a singa.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] In the Philippines, the fruit and tree are traditionally known as *lumbang*, after which Lumban, a lakeshore town in Laguna province, is named.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] Before the intrusion of non-native species, it was frequently used as a property-line manager because its silvery underleaf makes the tree easy to distinguish from a distance.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] In the state of Sabah, Malaysian Borneo, the Dusun tribes call the fruit *godou* and use it in tattoo-making as an optional ingredient for the ink.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] As recently as 1993 on the outlying islands of the kingdom of Tonga, candlenuts were chewed into sweet-scented emollient used during a traditional funerary ritual.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] They were used for making various sweet-smelling oils for the skin.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] In Australia, Aboriginal Australians used them for a variety of similar purposes.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] In Flores near Ende, it is called *kéloré* and used as a mordant for dyes with *Morinda citrifolia* (*mengkudu*).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] On the island of Rapa Iti in the Austral Islands, fish hooks were carved from the endocarp of the candlenut as a result of lacking other suitable material.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] These fish hooks were quite small and were used for catching certain species of fish, such as *Leptoscarus vaigiensis* (*Komokomo*) and *Stegastes fasciolatus* (*Nganga*).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] The plant is also known by the common names **candleberry**, **Indian walnut**, ***kemiri***, **varnish tree**, ***nuez de la India***, ***buah keras***, ***godou***, **kukui tree**, and ***rata kekuna***.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] It became Proto-Eastern-Malayo-Polynesian and Proto-Oceanic **tuRi* which is then reduplicated.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] Modern cognates including Fijian, Tongan, Rarotongan, and Niue *tui-tui*; and Hawaiian *kui-kui* or *kukui*.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] The Malay language in both has another name given to the nut which is *buah keras* (literally "hard fruit").
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] In Uganda, the seed is referred to as *kabakanjagala*, meaning "the king loves me".
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] In Maui, the *kukui* is a symbol of enlightenment, protection, and peace.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] Kamapuaʻa, the hog-man fertility demigod, was said to be able to transform into a *kukui* tree.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] One of the legends told of Kamapuaʻa: one day, a man beat his wife to death and buried her beneath Kamapuaʻa while he was in tree form.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] *Kukui* was named the state tree of Hawaii on 1 May 1959 due to its multitude of uses.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites-moluccanus] It also represents the island of Molokaʻi, whose symbolic color is the silvery green of the *kukui* leaf.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites] These monoecious, evergreen trees are perennials or semiperennials.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites] These are large trees, 15–40 m (49–131 ft) tall, with spreading, drooping, and rising branches.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites] The leaves are alternate, lobate, ovate to ovate-lanceolate with minute stipules.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites] They are pubescent on both sides when young, but in a later stage they become glabrous.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites] The inflorescence consists of terminal plumes of small, creamy white, bell-shaped, fragrant flowers, branching from the base.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites] The flowers are usually bisexual, with a solitary pistillate flower at the end of each major axis.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites] The staminate flowers are mostly longer and thinner than the pistillate flowers, with 17–32 glabrous stamens in four whorls.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites] The pistillate flowers have a superior ovary.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites] The fruits are rather large drupes with a fleshy exocarp and a thin, woody endocarp.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites] They vary in shape, according to the numbers of developed locules.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites] They contain oleiferous, poisonous seeds.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites] The oil has been used as a paraffin and lubricant, and as a constituent of varnish, paint, and soap.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites] Once poisonous substances are removed, it can be used as a cooking oil.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites] Some deciduous Chinese species are now classified under a separate genus *Vernicia*.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites] The name *Aleurites* is derived from the Ancient Greek: ἄλευρον meaning "wheaten flour" or "ground meal", because of the appearance of the lower surface of the leaf.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites] Linnaeus assigned the Latin feminine grammatical gender to the genus name *Aleurites*, as for example in the species name *Aleurites moluccana*.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites] The current International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants has standardized all genus names ending in *-ites* to use the masculine gender, so the correct name of the species *Aleurites moluccanus*.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites] The most widespread species is the candlenut (*Aleurites moluccanus*), occurring from tropical Asia and the Pacific, from India to China and Polynesia, Australia and New Zealand.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/aleurites] Some botanists only recognize two species, *A. moluccanus* and *A. rockinghamensis*.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] ***Prunus dulcis*** (Mill.) D.A.Webb, nom. illeg. non *Prunus dulcis* Rouchy) is a species of tree from the genus *Prunus*.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Along with the peach, it is classified in the subgenus *Amygdalus*, distinguished from the other subgenera by corrugations on the woody shell (endocarp) surrounding the seed.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The fruit of the almond is a drupe, consisting of an outer hull and a hard shell with the seed, which is not a true nut.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] *Shelling* almonds refers to removing the shell to reveal the seed.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Blanched almonds are unshelled almonds that have been treated with hot water to soften the outer skin, which is then removed to reveal the white embryo.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Once almonds are cleaned and processed, they can be stored for around a year if kept refrigerated; at higher temperatures they will become rancid more quickly.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Almonds are used in many cuisines, often featuring prominently in desserts, such as marzipan.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The almond tree prospers in a moderate Mediterranean climate with cool winter weather.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] It is rarely found wild in its original setting.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Almonds were one of the earliest domesticated fruit trees, due to the ability to produce quality offspring entirely from seed, without using suckers and cuttings.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Evidence of domesticated almonds in the Early Bronze Age has been found in the archeological sites of the Middle East, and subsequently across the Mediterranean region and similar arid climates with cool winters.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] California produces about 80% of the world's almond supply.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Due to high acreage and water demand for almond cultivation, and need for pesticides, California almond production may be unsustainable, especially during the persistent drought and heat from climate change in the 21st century.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Droughts in California have caused some producers to leave the industry, leading to lower supply and increased prices.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The almond is a deciduous tree growing to 3–4.5 metres (10–15 feet) in height, with a trunk of up to 30 centimetres (12 inches) in diameter.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The young twigs are green at first, becoming purplish where exposed to sunlight, then grey in their second year.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The leaves are 8–13 cm (3–5 in) long, with a serrated margin and a 2.5 cm (1 in) petiole.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The fragrant flowers are white to pale pink, 3–5 cm (1–2 in) diameter with five petals, produced singly or in pairs and appearing before the leaves in early spring.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Almond trees thrive in Mediterranean climates with warm, dry summers and mild, wet winters.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The optimal temperature for their growth is between 15 and 30 °C (59 and 86 °F) and the tree buds have a chilling requirement of 200 to 700 hours below 7.2 °C (45.0 °F) to break dormancy.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Almonds begin bearing an economic crop in the third year after planting.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Trees reach full bearing five to six years after planting.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The fruit matures in the autumn, 7–8 months after flowering.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The outer covering, consisting of an outer exocarp, or skin, and mesocarp, or flesh, fleshy in other members of *Prunus* such as the plum and cherry, is instead a thick, leathery, grey-green coat (with a downy exterior), called the hull.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Inside the hull is a woody endocarp which forms a reticulated, hard shell (like the outside of a peach pit) called the pyrena.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Inside the shell is the edible seed, commonly called a nut.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Generally, one seed is present, but occasionally two occur.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] After the fruit matures, the hull splits and separates from the shell, and an abscission layer forms between the stem and the fruit so that the fruit can fall from the tree.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] During harvest, mechanised tree shakers are used to expedite fruits falling to the ground for collection.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The almond was named *Amygdalus communis* by Carl Linnaeus in his Species plantarum in 1753.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] For the name 'Amygdalus' he referred to Gaspard Bauhin's *Pinax* (1623).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] In 1801 the species was for the first time placed in the genus *Prunus* by August Batsch.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] In that genus, the name *Prunus communis* was no longer available because in 1778 William Hudson had already assigned it to a taxon in which he included the plum (*Prunus domestica*).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Batsch thereupon named the species *Prunus amygdalus*, where 'amygdalus' is the old generic name and should therefore be treated as a noun in apposition.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Meanwhile, in 1768, Philip Miller had published the name of what he believed to be a second species of almond: *Amygdalus dulcis*.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] He mentioned Linnaeus' *Amygdalus communis* as the first species.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] It was not until 1967 that the combination *Prunus dulcis* was published for the almond by David Allardice Webb, on the assumption that *Amygdalus dulcis* was nothing more than a synonym of *Amygdalus communis*, and thus an available name for that species.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The epithet *dulcis* (1768) is older than *amygdalus* (1801) and would therefore have priority.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Webb noted that it was unfortunate that a species known for 165 years as *Prunus amygdalus* now had to be renamed under the rules of nomenclature.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] However, it later turned out that in 1967 the name *Prunus dulcis* was no longer available for the almond because it had already been used for a cherry in an 1878 publication by L'Abbé Rouchy.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The oldest valid combination in *Prunus* is therefore *Prunus amygdalus*.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] *dulcis* are predominantly sweet but some individual trees produce seeds that are somewhat more bitter.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The genetic basis for bitterness involves a single gene, the bitter flavour furthermore being recessive, both aspects making this trait easier to domesticate.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] *amara* are always bitter, as are the kernels from other species of genus *Prunus*, such as apricot, peach and cherry (although to a lesser extent).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The bitter almond is slightly broader and shorter than the sweet almond and contains about 50% of the fixed oil that occurs in sweet almonds.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] It contains the enzyme emulsin which, in the presence of water, acts on the two soluble glucosides amygdalin and prunasin yielding glucose, cyanide and the essential oil of bitter almonds, which is nearly pure benzaldehyde, the chemical causing the bitter flavour.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Bitter almonds may yield 4–9 milligrams of hydrogen cyanide per almond and contain 42 times higher amounts of cyanide than the trace levels found in sweet almonds.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The origin of cyanide content in bitter almonds is via the enzymatic hydrolysis of amygdalin.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] P450 monooxygenases are involved in the amygdalin biosynthetic pathway.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] A point mutation in a bHLH transcription factor prevents transcription of the two cytochrome P450 genes, resulting in the sweet kernel trait.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The word *almond* is a loanword from Old French *almande* or *alemande*, descended from Late Latin *amandula*, *amindula*, modified from Classical Latin *amygdala*, which is in turn borrowed from Ancient Greek *amygdálē* (ἀμυγδάλη) (cf. amygdala, an almond-shaped portion of the brain).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Late Old English had *amygdales* 'almonds'.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The adjective *amygdaloid* (literally 'like an almond, almond-like') is used to describe objects which are roughly almond-shaped, particularly a shape which is part way between a triangle and an ellipse.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] For example, the amygdala of the brain uses a direct borrowing of the Greek term *amygdalē*.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The precise origin of the almond is controversial due to estimates for its emergence across wide geographic regions.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Sources indicate that its origins were in an area stretching across Central Asia, Iran, Turkmenistan, Tajikistan, Kurdistan, Afghanistan, and Iraq, or in an eastern Asian subregion between Mongolia and Uzbekistan.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] In other assessments, both botanical and archaeological evidence indicates that almonds originated and were first cultivated in West Asia, particularly in countries of the Levant.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Most recent sources specified Iran and Anatolia (present day Turkey) as origin locations of the almond, with Iran as the main origin centre.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The wild form of domesticated almond grew in parts of the Levant.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Almond cultivation was spread by humans centuries ago along the shores of the Mediterranean Sea into northern Africa and southern Europe, and more recently to other world regions, notably California.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Selection of the sweet type from the many bitter types in the wild marked the beginning of almond domestication.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The wild ancestor of the almond used to breed the domesticated species is unknown.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The species *Prunus fenzliana* may be the most likely wild ancestor of the almond, in part because it is native to Armenia and western Azerbaijan, where it was apparently domesticated.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Wild almond species were grown by early farmers, "at first unintentionally in the garbage heaps, and later intentionally in their orchards".
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Almonds were one of the earliest domesticated fruit trees owing to their ability to be grown from seed, allowing their cultivation to have perhaps predated the advent of grafting.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Domesticated almonds appear in the Early Bronze Age (3000–2000 BCE), such as the archaeological sites of Numeira (Jordan), or possibly earlier.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] They were found in Tutankhamun's tomb in Egypt (c.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] 1325 BCE), probably imported from the Levant.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Ibn al-'Awwam's 12th-century *Book on Agriculture* includes an article on almond tree cultivation in Spain.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Of the European countries that the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh reported as cultivating almonds, Germany is the northernmost, though the domesticated form can be found as far north as Iceland.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Almond trees are small to medium-sized but commercial cultivars can be grafted onto a different root-stock to produce smaller trees.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Breeding programs have found a high shell-seal trait, which reduces insect damage and mold contamination.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The most widely planted varieties of almond are self-incompatible; hence these trees require pollen from a tree with different genetic characters to produce seeds.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Almond orchards therefore must grow mixtures of almond varieties.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] In addition, the pollen is transferred from flower to flower by insects; therefore commercial growers must ensure there are enough insects to perform this task.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The large scale of almond production in the U.S. creates a significant problem of providing enough pollinating insects.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Additional pollinating insects are therefore brought to the trees.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The pollination of California's almonds is the largest annual managed pollination event in the world, with over 1 million hives (nearly half of all beehives in the U.S.) being brought to the almond orchards each February.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Much of the supply of bees is managed by pollination brokers, who contract with migratory beekeepers from at least 49 states for the event.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] This business was heavily affected by colony collapse disorder at the turn of the 21st century, causing a nationwide shortage of honey bees and increasing the price of insect pollination.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] To partially protect almond growers from these costs, researchers at the Agricultural Research Service, part of the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA), developed self-pollinating almond trees that combine this character with quality characters such as a flavour and yield.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Almond trees can be attacked by an array of damaging microbes, fungal pathogens, plant viruses, and bacteria.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Pavement ants (*Tetramorium caespitum*), southern fire ants (*Solenopsis xyloni*), and thief ants (*Solenopsis molesta*) are seed predators.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] *Bryobia rubrioculus* mites are most known for their damage to this crop.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Almond production in California is concentrated mainly in the Central Valley, where the mild climate, rich soil, abundant sunshine and water supply make for ideal growing conditions.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Due to the persistent droughts in California in the early 21st century, it became more difficult to raise almonds in a sustainable manner.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The issue is complex because of the high amount of water needed to produce almonds: a single almond requires roughly 1.1 US gallons (0.92 imperial gallons; 4.2 litres) of water to grow properly.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Regulations related to water supplies are changing so some growers have destroyed their current almond orchards to replace with either younger trees or a different crop such as pistachio that needs less water.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] California almond farmers have promoted growing use of sustainable farming practices, including introduction of water-efficient irrigation technology, funding of honeybee health research, and productively using waste biomass (such as shells) in pursuit of a zero waste industry.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] In 2023, world production of almonds was 3.5 million tonnes, led by the United States with 51% of the total, followed by Spain and Australia as secondary producers (table).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Australia is the largest almond production region in the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Most of the country's almond orchards are located along the Murray River corridor in New South Wales, Victoria, or South Australia.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] In the Australian financial year 1 July 2024–30 June 2025, the national almond crop fell 5%, but increased in value by 20%, to a record A$1.3 billion.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] India was the second-largest export market, at 19,803 t (19,490 long tons; 21,829 short tons), a tonnage similar to that of the previous financial year.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] As of late February 2026, Australia was forecast to harvest a record almond crop of 167,000 t (164,000 long tons; 184,000 short tons) in the 2025–26 financial year.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Spain has diverse commercial cultivars of almonds grown in Catalonia, Valencia, Murcia, Andalusia, and Aragón regions, and the Balearic Islands.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The almond cultivar 'Marcona' is unique, having a kernel that is short, round, relatively sweet, and delicate in texture; it is marketed by name.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Its origin is unknown, but has been grown in Spain over centuries.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] In the U.S., production is concentrated in California where 400,000 ha (1,000,000 acres) and six different almond varieties were under cultivation in 2017, with a yield of 2.25 billion pounds (1.02 billion kilograms) of shelled almonds.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] California production is marked by a period of intense pollination during late winter by rented commercial bees transported by truck across the U.S. to almond groves, requiring more than half of the total U.S. commercial honeybee population.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The value of total U.S. exports of shelled almonds in 2016 was $3.2 billion.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] All commercially grown almonds sold as food in the U.S. are sweet cultivars.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Food and Drug Administration reported in 2010 that some fractions of imported sweet almonds were contaminated with bitter almonds, which contain cyanide.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Bitter almonds contain some 40 times the trace levels of cyanide found in sweet almonds.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Extract of bitter almond was once used medicinally, but even in small doses, its effects are severe or lethal, especially in children; the cyanide must be removed before consumption.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The acute oral lethal dose of cyanide for adult humans is reported to be 0.5–3.5 mg/kg (0.2–1.6 mg/lb) of body weight (approximately 50 bitter almonds for the average adult), so that for children consuming 5–10 bitter almonds may be fatal.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Symptoms of eating such almonds include vertigo and other typical cyanide poisoning effects.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Almonds may cause allergy or intolerance.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Cross-reactivity is common with peach allergens (lipid transfer proteins) and tree nut allergens.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Symptoms range from local signs and symptoms (e.g., oral allergy syndrome, contact urticaria) to systemic signs and symptoms including anaphylaxis (e.g., urticaria, angioedema, gastrointestinal and respiratory symptoms).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Almonds are susceptible to aflatoxin-producing moulds.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Aflatoxins are potent carcinogenic chemicals produced by moulds such as *Aspergillus flavus* and *Aspergillus parasiticus*.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The mould contamination may occur from soil, previously infested almonds, and almond pests such as navel-orange worm.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] High levels of mould growth typically appear as grey to black filament-like growth.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] It is unsafe to eat mould-infected tree nuts.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Some countries have strict limits on allowable levels of aflatoxin contamination of almonds and require adequate testing before the nuts can be marketed to their citizens.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The European Union, for example, introduced a requirement since 2007 that all almond shipments to the EU be tested for aflatoxin.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] If aflatoxin does not meet the strict safety regulations, either the entire consignment must be reprocessed to eliminate the aflatoxin or it must be destroyed.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] After tracing cases of salmonellosis to almonds, the USDA approved a proposal by the Almond Board of California to pasteurize almonds sold to the public.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] After publishing the rule in March 2007, the almond pasteurization program became mandatory for California companies effective 1 September 2007.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Raw, untreated California almonds have not been commercially available in the U.S. since then.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] California almonds labelled "raw" must be steam-pasteurized or chemically treated with propylene oxide (PPO).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] This does not apply to imported almonds or almonds sold from the grower directly to the consumer in small quantities.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The Almond Board of California states: "PPO residue dissipates after treatment".
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Environmental Protection Agency has reported: "Propylene oxide has been detected in fumigated food products; consumption of contaminated food is another possible route of exposure".
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] PPO is classified as Group 2B ("possibly carcinogenic to humans").
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The USDA-approved marketing order was challenged in court by organic farmers organized by the Cornucopia Institute, a Wisconsin-based farm policy research group which filed a lawsuit in September 2008.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] According to the institute, this almond marketing order has imposed significant financial burdens on small-scale and organic growers and damaged domestic almond markets.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] A federal judge dismissed the lawsuit in early 2009 on procedural grounds.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] In August 2010, a federal appeals court ruled that the farmers have a right to appeal the USDA regulation.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] In March 2013, the court vacated the suit on the basis that the objections should have been raised in 2007 when the regulation was first proposed.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Almonds are 4% water, 22% carbohydrates, 21% protein, and 50% fat (table).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Per 100 g, almonds contain dietary fiber (12 g), the monounsaturated fat, oleic acid (31 g), and the polyunsaturated fat, linoleic acid (12 g; table source).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Typical of nuts and seeds, almonds are a source of phytosterols, such as beta-sitosterol.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Almonds are included as a good source of protein among recommended healthy foods by the USDA.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] A 2016 review of clinical research indicated that regular consumption of almonds may reduce the risk of heart disease by lowering blood levels of LDL cholesterol.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] While the almond is often eaten on its own, raw or toasted, it is also a component of various dishes.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Almonds are available in many forms, such as whole, slivered, and ground into flour.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Almond pieces around 2–3 millimetres (1⁄16–1⁄8 in) in size, called "nibs", are used for special purposes such as decoration.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] A wide range of classic sweets feature almonds as a central ingredient.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Marzipan was developed in the Middle Ages.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Since the 19th century almonds have been used to make bread, almond butter, cakes and puddings, candied confections, almond cream-filled pastries, nougat, cookies (macaroons, biscotti and qurabiya), and cakes (financiers, Esterházy torte), and other sweets and desserts.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] In Saudi Arabia, almonds are a typical embellishment for the rice dish kabsa.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Spanish cookery uses almonds in sweet dishes as well as in savory ones, ground up to thicken sauces and stews.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Almonds can be processed into a milk substitute called almond milk; the nut's soft texture, mild flavour, and light colouring (when skinned) make for an efficient analog to dairy, and a soy-free choice for lactose intolerant people and vegans.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Raw, blanched, and lightly toasted almonds work well for different production techniques, some of which are similar to that of soy milk and some of which use no heat, resulting in raw milk.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Almond milk, along with almond butter and almond oil, are versatile products used in both sweet and savoury dishes.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] In Moroccan cuisine, sharbat billooz, a common beverage, is made by blending blanched almonds with milk, sugar and other flavourings.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Almond flour or ground almond meal combined with sugar or honey as marzipan is often used as a gluten-free alternative to wheat flour in cooking and baking.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Almonds contain polyphenols in their skins consisting of flavonols, flavan-3-ols, hydroxybenzoic acids and flavanones analogous to those of certain fruits and vegetables.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] These phenolic compounds and almond skin prebiotic dietary fibre have commercial interest as food additives or dietary supplements.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Historically, almond syrup was an emulsion of sweet and bitter almonds, usually made with barley syrup (orgeat syrup) or in a syrup of orange flower water and sugar, often flavoured with a synthetic aroma of almonds.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Orgeat syrup is an important ingredient in the Mai Tai and many other Tiki drinks.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Due to the cyanide found in bitter almonds, modern syrups generally are produced only from sweet almonds.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Such syrup products do not contain significant levels of hydrocyanic acid, so are generally considered safe for human consumption.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Almonds are a rich source of oil, with 50% of kernel dry mass as fat (whole almond nutrition table).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] In relation to total dry mass of the kernel, almond oil contains 32% monounsaturated oleic acid (an omega-9 fatty acid), 13% linoleic acid (a polyunsaturated omega-6 essential fatty acid), and 10% saturated fatty acid (mainly as palmitic acid).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Linolenic acid, a polyunsaturated omega-3 fat, is not present (table).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] When almond oil is analyzed separately and expressed per 100 grams as a reference mass, the oil provides 3,700 kJ (884 kcal) of food energy, 8 grams of saturated fat (81% of which is palmitic acid), 70 grams of oleic acid, and 17 grams of linoleic acid (oil table).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The almond is highly revered in some cultures.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] In the Bible, the almond is mentioned ten times, beginning with Genesis 43:11, where it is described as "among the best of fruits".
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] In Numbers 17, Levi is chosen from the other tribes of Israel by Aaron's rod, which brought forth almond flowers.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] In Jeremiah 1:11–12, the vision of an almond branch conveys a wordplay in Hebrew between *shaqed* (almond) and *shoqed* (watching), symbolizing God's vigilant commitment to fulfill His word.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Many Sephardic Jews give five almonds to each guest before special occasions like weddings.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] Similarly, Christian symbolism often uses almond branches as a symbol of the virgin birth of Jesus; paintings and icons often include almond-shaped haloes encircling the Christ Child and as a symbol of Mary.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The word "luz", which appears in Genesis 30:37, sometimes translated as "hazel", may actually be derived from the Aramaic name for almond (Luz), and is translated as such in the New International Version and other versions of the Bible.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/almond] The Entrance of the flower (*La entrada de la flor*) is an event celebrated on 1 February in Torrent, Spain, in which the clavarios and members of the Confrerie of the Mother of God deliver a branch of the first-blooming almond-tree to the Virgin.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek was the language of Homer and of fifth-century Athenian historians, playwrights, and philosophers.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] It has contributed many words to English vocabulary and has been a standard subject of study in educational institutions of the Western world since the Renaissance.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] This article primarily contains information about the Epic and Classical periods of the language, which are the best-attested periods and considered most typical of Ancient Greek.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek comprised several dialects, such as Attic, Ionic, Doric, Aeolic, and Arcadocypriot; among them, Attic Greek became the basis of Koine Greek.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Just like Koine is often included in Ancient Greek, conversely, Mycenaean Greek is usually treated separately and not always included in Ancient Greek – reflecting the fact that Greek in the first millennium BC is considered prototypical of Ancient Greek.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek was a pluricentric language, divided into many dialects.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] The main dialect groups are Attic and Ionic, Aeolic, Arcadocypriot, and Doric, many of them with several subdivisions.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Some dialects are found in standardized literary forms in literature, while others are attested only in inscriptions.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] There are also several historical forms.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Homeric Greek is a literary form of Archaic Greek (derived primarily from Ionic and Aeolic) used in the epic poems, the *Iliad* and the *Odyssey*, and in later poems by other authors.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Homeric Greek had significant differences in grammar and pronunciation from Classical Attic and other Classical-era dialects.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] The origins, early form and development of the Hellenic language family are not well understood because of a lack of contemporaneous evidence.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Several theories exist about what Hellenic dialect groups may have existed between the divergence of early Greek-like speech from the common Proto-Indo-European language and the Classical period.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] They have the same general outline but differ in some of the detail.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] The only attested dialect from this period is Mycenaean Greek, but its relationship to the historical dialects and the historical circumstances of the times imply that the overall groups already existed in some form.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Scholars assume that major Ancient Greek period dialect groups developed no later than 1120 BC, at the time of the Dorian invasions—and that their first appearances as precise alphabetic writing began in the 8th century BC.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] The invasion would not be "Dorian" unless the invaders had some cultural relationship to the historical Dorians.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] The invasion is known to have displaced population to the later Attic-Ionic regions, who regarded themselves as descendants of the population displaced by or contending with the Dorians.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] The Greeks of this period believed there were three major divisions of all Greek people – Dorians, Aeolians, and Ionians (including Athenians), each with their own defining and distinctive dialects.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Allowing for their oversight of Arcadian, an obscure mountain dialect, and Cypriot, far from the center of Greek scholarship, this division of people and language is quite similar to the results of modern archaeological-linguistic investigation.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] (Southern Italy and Sicily) in the classical period.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] West vs. non-West Greek is the strongest-marked and earliest division, with non-West in subsets of Ionic-Attic (or Attic-Ionic) and Aeolic vs.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Arcadocypriot, or Aeolic and Arcado-Cypriot vs.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Arcadocypriot apparently descended more closely from the Mycenaean Greek of the Bronze Age.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Boeotian Greek had come under a strong Northwest Greek influence, and can in some respects be considered a transitional dialect, as exemplified in the poems of the Boeotian poet Pindar who wrote in Doric with a small Aeolic admixture.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Thessalian likewise had come under Northwest Greek influence, though to a lesser degree.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Pamphylian Greek, spoken in a small area on the southwestern coast of Anatolia and little preserved in inscriptions, may be either a fifth major dialect group, or it is Mycenaean Greek overlaid by Doric, with a non-Greek native influence.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Based on the conclusions drawn by several studies and findings such as Pella curse tablet, Emilio Crespo and most scholars suggest that ancient Macedonian was a Northwest Doric dialect, which shares isoglosses with its neighboring Thessalian dialects spoken in northeastern Thessaly.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Some have also suggested an Aeolic Greek classification.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] For example, fragments of the works of the poet Sappho from the island of Lesbos are in Aeolian.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Most of the dialect sub-groups listed above had further subdivisions, generally equivalent to a city-state and its surrounding territory, or to an island.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Doric notably had several intermediate divisions as well, into Island Doric (including Cretan Doric), Southern Peloponnesus Doric (including Laconian, the dialect of Sparta), and Northern Peloponnesus Doric (including Corinthian).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] All the groups were represented by colonies beyond Greece proper as well, and these colonies generally developed local characteristics, often under the influence of settlers or neighbors speaking different Greek dialects.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] After the conquests of Alexander the Great in the late 4th century BC, a new international dialect known as Koine or Common Greek developed, largely based on Attic Greek, but with influence from other dialects.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] This dialect slowly replaced most of the older dialects, although the Doric dialect has survived in the Tsakonian language, which is spoken in the region of modern Sparta.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Doric has also passed down its aorist terminations into most verbs of Demotic Greek.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] By about the 6th century AD, the Koine had slowly metamorphosed into Medieval Greek.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Phrygian is an extinct Indo-European language of West and Central Anatolia, which is regarded by current consensus to have been closely related to Greek.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Among Indo-European branches with living descendants, Greek is often argued to have the closest genetic ties with Armenian (see also Graeco-Armenian) and Indo-Iranian languages (see Graeco-Aryan).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek differs from Proto-Indo-European (PIE) and other Indo-European languages in certain ways.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] In phonotactics, ancient Greek words could end only in a vowel or /n s r/; final stops were lost, as in γάλα "milk", compared with γάλακτος "of milk" (genitive).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] The pronunciation of Ancient Greek was very different from that of Modern Greek.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek had long and short vowels; many diphthongs; double and single consonants; voiced, voiceless, and aspirated stops; and a pitch accent.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] In Modern Greek, all vowels and consonants are short.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Many vowels and diphthongs once pronounced distinctly are pronounced as /i/ (iotacism).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Some of the stops and glides in diphthongs have become fricatives, and the pitch accent has changed to a stress accent.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Many of the changes took place in the Koine Greek period.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] The writing system of Modern Greek, however, does not reflect all pronunciation changes.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] The examples below represent Attic Greek in the 5th century BC.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Ancient pronunciation cannot be reconstructed with certainty, but Greek from the period is well documented, and there is little disagreement among linguists as to the general nature of the sounds that the letters represent.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] /oː/ raised to [uː], probably by the 4th century BC.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Greek, like all of the older Indo-European languages, is highly inflected.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] It is highly archaic in its preservation of Proto-Indo-European forms.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] In ancient Greek, nouns (including proper nouns) have five cases (nominative, genitive, dative, accusative, and vocative), three genders (masculine, feminine, and neuter), and three numbers (singular, dual, and plural).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Verbs have four moods (indicative, imperative, subjunctive, and optative) and three voices (active, middle, and passive), as well as three persons (first, second, and third) and various other forms.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Verbs are conjugated through seven combinations of tenses and aspect (generally simply called "tenses"): the present, future, and imperfect are imperfective in aspect; the aorist, present perfect, pluperfect and future perfect are perfective in aspect.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Most tenses display all four moods and three voices, although there is no future subjunctive or imperative.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Also, there is no imperfect subjunctive, optative or imperative.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] The infinitives and participles correspond to the finite combinations of tense, aspect, and voice.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] The indicative of past tenses adds (conceptually, at least) a prefix /e-/, called the augment.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] This was probably originally a separate word, meaning something like "then", added because tenses in PIE had primarily aspectual meaning.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] The augment is added to the indicative of the aorist, imperfect, and pluperfect, but not to any of the other forms of the aorist (no other forms of the imperfect and pluperfect exist).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] The two kinds of augment in Greek are syllabic and quantitative.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] The syllabic augment is added to stems beginning with consonants, and simply prefixes *e* (stems beginning with *r*, however, add *er*).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Some verbs augment irregularly; the most common variation is *e* → *ei*.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] The irregularity can be explained diachronically by the loss of *s* between vowels, or that of the letter *w*, which affected the augment when it was word-initial.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] In verbs with a preposition as a prefix, the augment is placed not at the start of the word, but between the preposition and the original verb.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] For example, προσ(-)βάλλω (I attack) goes to προσ**έ**βαλoν in the aorist.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] However compound verbs consisting of a prefix that is not a preposition retain the augment at the start of the word: αὐτο(-)μολῶ goes to **ηὐ**τομόλησα in the aorist.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Following Homer's practice, the augment is sometimes not made in poetry, especially epic poetry.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] The augment sometimes substitutes for reduplication; see below.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Almost all forms of the perfect, pluperfect, and future perfect reduplicate the initial syllable of the verb stem.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Irregular duplication can be understood diachronically.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] For example, *lambanō* (root *lab*) has the perfect stem *eilēpha* (not **lelēpha*) because it was originally *slambanō*, with perfect *seslēpha*, becoming *eilēpha* through compensatory lengthening.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Reduplication is also visible in the present tense stems of certain verbs.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] These stems add a syllable consisting of the root's initial consonant followed by *i*.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] A nasal stop appears after the reduplication in some verbs.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] The earliest extant examples of ancient Greek writing (c.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] 1450 BC) are in the syllabic script Linear B.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Beginning in the 8th century BC, however, the Greek alphabet became standard, albeit with some variation among dialects.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Early texts are written in boustrophedon style, but left-to-right became standard during the classic period.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Modern editions of ancient Greek texts are usually written with accents and breathing marks, interword spacing, modern punctuation, and sometimes mixed case, but these were all introduced later.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] The beginning of Apology by Plato exemplifies Attic Greek from the Classical period of ancient Greek.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] How you, men of Athens, are feeling under the power of my accusers, I do not know: actually, even I myself almost forgot who I was because of them, they spoke so persuasively.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] And yet, loosely speaking, nothing they have said is true.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] The study of Ancient Greek in European countries in addition to Latin occupied an important place in the syllabus from the Renaissance until the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] This was true as well in the United States, where many of the nation's founders received a classically based education.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Latin was emphasized in American colleges, but Greek also was required in the colonial and early national eras, and the study of ancient Greece became increasingly popular in the mid-to-late nineteenth century, the age of American philhellenism.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] In particular, female intellectuals of the era designated the mastering of ancient Greek as essential in becoming a "woman of letters".
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is still taught as a compulsory or optional subject especially at traditional or elite schools throughout Europe, such as public schools and grammar schools in the United Kingdom.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] In 2006/07, 15,000 pupils studied ancient Greek in Germany according to the Federal Statistical Office of Germany, and 280,000 pupils studied it in Italy.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] It is a compulsory subject alongside Latin in the humanities branch of the Spanish Baccalaureate.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is taught at most major universities worldwide, often combined with Latin as part of the study of classics.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] In 2010 it was offered in three primary schools in the UK, to boost children's language skills, and was one of seven foreign languages which primary schools could teach 2014 as part of a major drive to boost education standards.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is taught as a compulsory subject in all gymnasiums and lyceums in Greece.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] It appears to have ceased in 2010, having failed to gain the recognition and acceptance of teachers.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Its first issue appeared in April 2015 as an annex to *Hebdomada Aenigmatum*.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Alfred Rahlfs included a preface, a short history of the Septuagint text, and other front matter translated into ancient Greek in his 1935 edition of the Septuagint; Robert Hanhart also included the introductory remarks to the 2006 revised Rahlfs–Hanhart edition in the language as well.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] *Akropolis World News* reports weekly a summary of the most important news in ancient Greek.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is also used by organizations and individuals, mainly Greek, who wish to denote their respect, admiration or preference for the use of this language.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] This use is sometimes considered graphical, nationalistic or humorous.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] In any case, the fact that modern Greeks can still wholly or partly understand texts written in non-archaic forms of ancient Greek shows the affinity of the modern Greek language to its ancestral predecessor.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is often used in the coinage of modern technical terms in the European languages: see English words of Greek origin.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-greek] Latinized forms of ancient Greek roots are used in many of the scientific names of species and in scientific terminology.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] The islands in Eastern Polynesia have been characterized by the continuities among their cultures, and the short migration period would be an explanation of this result.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Diversified agroforestry and aquaculture provided sustenance for Native Hawaiian cuisine.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Tropical materials were adopted for housing.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Elaborate temples (called *heiau*) were constructed from the lava rocks available.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] The rich natural resources supported a relatively dense population, organized by a ruling class and social system with religious leaders.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Captain James Cook made the first known European contact with ancient Hawaiians in 1778.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] He was followed by many other people globally.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] There have been changing views about initial Polynesian arrival to Hawai'i.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Radiocarbon dating in Hawai'i initially indicated a possible settlement as early as 124 CE.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Patrick Vinton Kirch's early books on Hawaiian archeology date the first Polynesian settlements to about 300 CE with more recent suggestions by Kirch of 600 CE.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Other theories suggest dating as late as 700–800 CE.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] In 2010, researchers announced new findings using revised, high-precision radiocarbon dating based on more reliable samples than were previously used in many dating studies.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] This new data indicates that the period of eastern and northern Polynesian arrival took place much later, in a shorter time frame of two waves: the "earliest in the Society Islands c.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] 1025–1120, four centuries later than previously assumed; then after 70–265 years, dispersal continued in one major pulse to all remaining islands c.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] 1190–1290." According to this research, the migration and arrival to the Hawaiian Islands took place c.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] This rapid migration is believed to account for the "remarkable uniformity of East Polynesia culture, biology and language".
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Early people brought along with them clothing, plants (called "canoe plants") and livestock and established settlements along the coasts and larger valleys.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Upon their arrival, the settlers grew *kalo* (taro), *maiʻa* (banana), *niu* (coconut), *ulu* (breadfruit), and raised *puaʻa* (pork), *moa* (chicken), and *ʻīlio* (poi dog), although these meats were eaten less often than fruits, vegetables, and seafood.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Popular condiments included *paʻakai* (salt), ground kukui nut, *limu* (seaweed), and *ko* (sugarcane) which was used as both a sweet and a medicine.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] In addition to the foods they brought, the settlers also acquired *ʻuala* (sweet potato), which began to be cultivated across Polynesia around the year 1000 or earlier, with the earliest evidence of cultivation in Hawaii around 1300.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] The sweet potato is native to South America.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Recently, an analysis of the DNA of 1,245 sweet potato varieties from Asia and the Americas was done, and researchers found a genetic link that proves the root made it to Polynesia from the Andes around 1100.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] The findings, published in the *Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences*, offer more evidence that ancient Polynesians may have interacted with people in South America long before the Europeans set foot on the continent.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] The Pacific rat accompanied humans on their journey to Hawaiʻi.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] David Burney argues that humans, along with the vertebrate animals they brought with them (pigs, dogs, chickens and rats), caused many native species of birds, plants and large land snails to become extinct in the process of colonization.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Estuaries and streams were adapted into fishponds by early Polynesian settlers, as long ago as 500 CE or earlier.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Packed earth and cut stone were used to create habitat, making ancient Hawaiian aquaculture among the most advanced of the original peoples of the Pacific.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] A notable example is the Menehune Fishpond dating from at least 1,000 years ago, at Alekoko (Kaua'i).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] At the time of Captain James Cook's arrival, there were at least 360 fishponds producing 2,000,000 pounds (900,000 kg) of fish per year.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Over the course of the last millennium, Hawaiians undertook "large-scale canal-fed pond field irrigation" projects for *kalo* (taro) cultivation.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] The new settlers built *hale* (homes) and *heiau* (temples).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Archaeologists currently believe that the first settlements were on the southern end of the Big Island of Hawaiʻi and that they quickly extended northwards, along the seacoasts and the easily accessible river valleys.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] As the population increased, settlements were made further inland.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] With the islands being so small, the population was very dense.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Before European contact, the population had reached somewhere in the range of 200,000 to 1,000,000 people.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] After contact with the Europeans, however, the population steeply dropped due to various diseases including smallpox.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] The Wai'ahukini Rockshelter, site H8, lies within a lava tube about 600 feet (183 m) inland from the shore on the southern part of the island of Hawai'i.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Based on the lack of light and space necessary for normal living conditions, it was unlikely that site H8 was used as a dwelling.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Excavations of site H8 began in 1954 by William J.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Bonk and students from the University of Hawaii, Hilo, and concluded in 1958.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Excavation of the site revealed eight fireplaces at varying depths, as well as 1671 artifacts which included faunal remains, fishhooks, and lithic materials made of basalt and volcanic glass.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] The distribution of artifacts in site H8 indicated that it was continuously used as a fishing shelter until the eruption of Mauna Loa in 1868.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] An early estimation of the site's initial occupation was A.D.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] 750 by Emory and Sinoto in 1969, but a more recent study using updated radiocarbon dating methods suggested a much later date, somewhere within the mid-14th century.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Located on the island of Moloka'i, the Hālawa Dune Site was first discovered in 1964 and consists of two mounds.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] In the summer of 1970, Patrick Vinton Kirch performed excavations on the larger of the two mounds, Mound B, revealing six major layers.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Within the fourth layer were artifacts, faunal remains, and house foundations.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Of the 496 artifacts unearthed in this layer, the most significant included fishhooks and adzes.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] A traditional town of ancient Hawaiʻi included several structures.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Ancient Hawaiʻi was a caste society developed from ancestral Polynesians.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Hawaiian youth learned life skills and religion at home, often with grandparents.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] For "bright" children a system of apprenticeship existed in which very young students would begin learning a craft or profession by assisting an expert, or *kahuna*.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] As spiritual powers were perceived by Hawaiians to imbue all of nature, experts in many fields of work were known as *kahuna*, a term commonly understood to mean *priest*.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] The various types of *kahuna* passed on knowledge of their profession, be it in "genealogies, or *mele*, or herb medicine, or canoe building, or land boundaries", etc. by involving and instructing apprentices in their work.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] More formal schools existed for the study of *hula*, and likely for the study of higher levels of sacred knowledge.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] The *kahuna* took the apprentice into his household as a member of the family, although often "the tutor was a relative".
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] During a religious "graduation" ceremony, "the teacher consecrated the pupil, who thereafter was one with the teacher in psychic relationship as definite and obligatory as blood relationship".
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Like the children learning from their grandparents, children who were apprentices learned by watching and participating in daily life.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Children were discouraged from asking questions in traditional Hawaiian culture.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] In Hawaiian ideology, one does not "own" the land, but merely dwells on it.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] The belief was that both the land and the gods were immortal.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] This then informed the belief that land was also godly, and therefore above mortal and ungodly humans, and humans therefore could not own land.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] The Hawaiians thought that all land belonged to the gods (*akua*).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] The *aliʻi* were believed to be "managers" of land.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] That is, they controlled those who worked on the land, the *makaʻāinana*.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] On the death of one chief and the accession of another, lands were re-apportioned—some of the previous "managers" would lose their lands, and others would gain them.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Lands were also re-apportioned when one chief defeated another and re-distributed the conquered lands as rewards to his warriors.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] In practice, commoners had some security against capricious re-possession of their houses and farms.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] They were usually left in place, to pay tribute and supply labor to a new chief, under the supervision of a new *konohiki*, or overseer.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] This system of land tenure has similarities with the feudal system prevalent in Europe during the Middle Ages.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] The ancient Hawaiians had the *ahupuaʻa* as their source of water management.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Each *ahupuaʻa* was a sub-division of land from the mountain to the sea.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] The Hawaiians used the water from the rain that ran through the mountains as a form of irrigation.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Hawaiians also settled around these parts of the land because of the farming that was done.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Religion held ancient Hawaiian society together, affecting habits, lifestyles, work methods, social policy and law.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] The legal system was based on religious *kapu*, or taboos.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] There was a correct way to live, to worship, and even to eat.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Examples of *kapu* included the provision that men and women could not eat together (ʻAikapu religion).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Fishing was limited to specified seasons of the year.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] The shadow of the *aliʻi* must not be touched as it was stealing his *mana*.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] The rigidity of the *kapu* system might have come from a second wave of migrations in 1000–1300 from which different religions and systems were shared between Hawaiʻi and the Society Islands.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Had Hawaiʻi been influenced by the Tahitian chiefs, the *kapu* system would have become stricter, and the social structure would have changed.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Human sacrifice would have become a part of their new religious observance, and the *aliʻi* would have gained more power over the counsel of experts on the islands.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] The Hawaiian mystical worldview allows for different gods and spirits to imbue any aspect of the natural world.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] From this mystical perspective, in addition to his presence in lightning and rainbows, the god of light and life, Kāne, can be present in rain and clouds and a peaceful breeze (typically the "home" of Lono).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Although all food and drink had religious significance to the ancient Hawaiians, special cultural emphasis was placed on *ʻawa* (*kava*) due to its narcotic properties.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] This root-based beverage, a psychoactive and a relaxant, was used to consecrate meals and commemorate ceremonies.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] It is often referred to in Hawaiian chant.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Different varieties of the root were used by different castes, and the brew served as an "introduction to mysticism".
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] The four biggest islands, the island of Hawaiʻi, Maui, Kauaʻi and Oʻahu were generally ruled by their own *aliʻi nui* (supreme ruler) with lower ranking subordinate chiefs called *aliʻi ʻaimoku*, ruling individual districts with land agents called *konohiki*.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] All these dynasties were interrelated and regarded all the Hawaiian people (and possibly all humans) as descendants of legendary parents, Wākea (symbolizing the air) and his wife Papa (symbolizing the earth).
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Up to the late eighteenth century, the island of Hawaiʻi had been ruled by one line descended from Umi-a-Liloa.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] At the death of Keaweʻīkekahialiʻiokamoku, a lower ranking chief, Alapainui, overthrew the two sons of the former ruler who were next in line as the island's *aliʻi nui*.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Assuming five to ten generations per century, the *Aliʻi ʻAimoku* dynasties were around three to six centuries old at 1800 CE.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] The Tahitian settlement of the Hawaiian islands is believed to have taken place in the thirteenth century.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] The *aliʻi* and other social castes were presumably established during this period.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] By chance in January 1778, British Captain James Cook encountered the Hawaiian Islands while crossing the Pacific during his third voyage of exploration.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] He landed first on Kauaʻi, then Niʻihau before leaving the vicinity to continue his mission to explore the Pacific coast of North America.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Cook's two ships returned to the islands in November to re-supply, first sailing along the coast of Maui before eventually reaching an anchorage at Kealakekua Bay on Hawaii island.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Some Hawaiians believed Cook was a sign from their god Lono.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Cook's mast and sails coincidentally resembled the emblem (a mast and sheet of white *kapa*) that symbolized Lono in their religious rituals; the ships arrived during the *Makahiki* season dedicated to peace.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Later, Cook was killed as he attempted to kidnap Kalaniʻōpuʻu, the ruling chief of the island of Hawaii and left behind on the beach by his retreating sailors.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] The British demanded that his body be returned, but the Hawaiians had already performed funerary rituals of their tradition.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] This first European contact with the Hawaiian islands marked the beginning of the end of the Ancient Hawaiʻi period.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] After Cook's visit and the publication of several books relating his voyages, the Hawaiian Islands attracted European and American explorers, traders, and whalers, who found the islands to be a convenient harbor and source of supplies.
[src:aleurites-moluccanus/ancient-hawaii] Within a few decades Kamehameha I used European warfare tactics and some firearms and cannons to unite the islands into the Kingdom of Hawaiʻi.
